  <title>Functions</title>

<commentary audience="instructor"><title>Overview</title>
<p>In this Lesson we introduce the basic notation and terminology for functions. Students have already seen many examples of functions in their study of linear and quadratic equations, so point out that this lesson is more about a new language than about new ideas.</p>

<p>This might be a good time to review the process of reading the Lesson. Ask students to bring their textbook to class, and go over the reading with them. Point out the sub-heads for each section, and the summary boxes. Go over the Reading Questions and each Exercise with the class. There will probably be some confusion about whether a table represents a function: is it allowed to have two different inputs with the same output?</p>

<p>Then go over Activity 2. You could ask the class to hand in either or both of Activities 1 and 3, perhaps as a group project. Students usually find this material relatively easy after the units on quadratic models.</p></commentary>

<activity><title>Epidemics</title>
    
